sec.p:
We aimed to synthesise the outcomes of food supplementation experiments in several bird reproductive parameters by using quantitative meta-analyses. We found mostly positive effects of food supplementation experiments on bird reproduction, indicating that within the pool of bird species and environments reviewed, extra food is often allocated to immediate reproduction. The effects of supplementary food were still variable across reproductive parameters; this is consistent with the idea that varying energetic costs are associated with different stages of the breeding cycle, and it also shows that bird species have evolved different life-history strategies to cope with environmental variability in food supply. The average increase in bird breeding success (response ratio: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
